abstract: From candy to kombucha to our national mood, acidity is everywhere.
snippet: From candy to kombucha to our national mood, acidity is everywhere.
lead_paragraph: SOUR IS A FLINCH, the taste that betrays. Only the most stoic among us can keep a straight face, mouth unpuckered, after a suck of lemon, say, or a piece of umeboshi, Japanese salted sour plum — which can contain as much as three times a lemon’s citric acid, more than any other fruit — or the first slow, meditative chew of Super Hiper Ácido bubble gum from Ecuador, before its cache of sour powder detonates and any residue of flavor is obliterated by sheer physical recoil.

abstract: Mr. O’Rourke said Tuesday that he had failed to acknowledge the advantages of running for president as a white man who has led a life of relative privilege.
snippet: Mr. O’Rourke said Tuesday that he had failed to acknowledge the advantages of running for president as a white man who has led a life of relative privilege.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For the first eight weeks of his presidential bid, Beto O’Rourke did what a presidential candidate is expected to do: He campaigned. Driving more than 6,150 miles across 14 states, as logged by his campaign, he held more than 152 town hall meetings and visited 32 college campuses, answering more than 1,000 questions.

abstract: Senator Elizabeth Warren said she would not participate in a Fox News town hall-style event, but some of her 2020 Democratic rivals have taken up the network’s offer.
snippet: Senator Elizabeth Warren said she would not participate in a Fox News town hall-style event, but some of her 2020 Democratic rivals have taken up the network’s offer.
lead_paragraph: Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts on Tuesday broke from her Democratic rivals by declining to participate in a Fox News town hall, denouncing the cable news channel as “a hate-for-profit racket” that seeks to turns Americans against one another.

headline_main: A Debut Novel Set on the Brooding, Remote Kamchatka Peninsula

abstract: Adventurous directors and galvanizing performances made for unexpected — and very welcome — departures on what once felt like the Staid White Way.
snippet: Adventurous directors and galvanizing performances made for unexpected — and very welcome — departures on what once felt like the Staid White Way.
lead_paragraph: With “Hadestown” and “Burn This” on the bill, and “The Ferryman,” “Gary” and even “Oklahoma!” leaving blood on the floor, it was not a Broadway season for the faint of heart. Yet as “Tootsie” and “The Prom” demonstrated, audiences — and Tony Award nominators — were ready to laugh as well.

abstract: John Singleton put black lives on the big screen.
snippet: John Singleton put black lives on the big screen.
lead_paragraph: For those of us who grew up black in the 1980s, going to the movies meant picking a character to identify with and pretending that person was black. It was a great era for film: There was “The Breakfast Club” and “Ferris Bueller’s Day Off,” “Back to the Future” and “Top Gun.” But black people were almost entirely invisible in those worlds.

abstract: 25 years ago was yesterday and a million years ago.
snippet: 25 years ago was yesterday and a million years ago.
lead_paragraph: We tend to recall the past not on its own merits but in terms of what it lacked in retrospect. Virtually the entire period of planetary existence is lumped into the condescending unit “before Christ.” Our hominid ancestors are described not as astonishing animals that harnessed the destructive force of fire, but “prehistoric” — people who didn’t know how to write.

abstract: The representative from New York inspired a comic book anthology that arrives in stores on Wednesday.
snippet: The representative from New York inspired a comic book anthology that arrives in stores on Wednesday.
lead_paragraph: Is Representative Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez of New York the biggest comic book character of 2019? Her story has all the twists of a comic book origin: She’s a former bartender and activist turned congresswoman; she’s a confident public speaker and a social-media whiz  (where she once quoted from the “Watchmen” graphic novel); and she’s a champion for progressive issues and the environment.

abstract: From the perky girl next door in the 1950s to the woman next door in 1960s sex comedies, Ms. Day was the most popular film actress since Shirley Temple.
snippet: From the perky girl next door in the 1950s to the woman next door in 1960s sex comedies, Ms. Day was the most popular film actress since Shirley Temple.
lead_paragraph: Doris Day, the freckle-faced movie actress whose irrepressible personality and golden voice made her America’s top box-office star in the early 1960s, died on Monday at her home in Carmel Valley, Calif. She was 97.
